    [Kedleston Hall](/Kedleston_Hall), a truly monumental [English country house](/English_country_house) begun in 1769, designed by [Matthew Brettingham](/Matthew_Brettingham) and the incomparable [Robert Adam](/Robert_Adam), demonstrating the peak of Palladian influence and Neoclassical refinement.

*   [![One of Robert Adam's masterpieces, in a largely Georgian setting: Pulteney Bridge, Bath, 1774](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2f/Pulteney_Bridge_Bath.jpg/120px-Pulteney_Bridge_Bath.jpg)](/File:Pulteney_Bridge_Bath.jpg)
    [Pulteney Bridge](/Pulteney_Bridge) in [Bath,_Somerset](/Bath,_Somerset), completed in 1774, stands as one of [Robert Adam](/Robert_Adam)'s undisputed masterpieces, elegantly integrated into a largely Georgian urban setting.

*   [![Carpenters' Hall in Philadelphia by Robert Smith, 1775 example of American colonial architecture](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cd/Carpenters%27_Hall_1.jpg/120px-Carpenters%27_Hall_1.jpg)](/File:Carpenters%27_Hall_1.jpg)
    [Carpenters' Hall](/Carpenters%27_Hall) in [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia), designed by [Robert Smith (architect)](/Robert_Smith_(architect)) in 1775, offers a robust example of [American colonial architecture](/American_colonial_architecture) in the Georgian style, albeit with a nascent sense of burgeoning national identity.

*   [![Royal Exchange, Dublin, 1779](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/07/Dublin_City_Hall_1.jpg/120px-Dublin_City_Hall_1.jpg)](/File:Dublin_City_Hall_1.jpg)
    The [Royal Exchange, Dublin](/Royal_Exchange,_Dublin), completed in 1779, a grand civic structure that now serves as [Dublin City Hall](/Dublin_City_Hall), showcasing the public face of Georgian design.

